	<LINE>SUGGESTIONS TO THE PUBLIC, &amp;r.</LINE>
	<LINE>Facility is given to the Post Office in the discharge of its daily duties, and</LINE>
	<LINE>greater security afforded to the public, by careful attention to the following</LINE>
	<LINE>recoiuiuendations : —</LINE>
	<LINE>1st. To post all letters, &amp;c. , as early as practicable, esiiecially when</LINE>
	<LINE>sent in large numbers, as is frequently the case with newspapers</LINE>
	<LINE>and cii'culars. The trouble of the office is tuuch diminished if cir-</LINE>
	<LINE>culars, before being posted, be tied in bundles, with the addresses</LINE>
	<LINE>all in one direction.</LINE>
	<LINE>2nd. To make the addresses legible and complete, giving the name of the</LINE>
	<LINE>post town ; and if there be more than one town in the kingdom of</LINE>
	<LINE>that name, or if the post town be not well known, adding the</LINE>
	<LINE>name of the county.</LINE>
	<LINE>3rd. To see that every letter, newspaper, or other packet, sent by post is</LINE>
	<LINE>securely folded and fastened. When postage stamps are remitted,</LINE>
	<LINE>they should be enclosed in paper sufficiently thick to prevent them</LINE>
	<LINE>from being seen or felt through the covei\</LINE>
	<LINE>4th. Never to send money or any other article of value through the post,</LINE>
	<LINE>except either by means of a taonti/ order or in a registered letter.</LINE>
	<LINE>5th. When complaint is made of letters or newspapers lost, miscarried,</LINE>
	<LINE>or delaj'ed, to furnish information to the Secretary as precise as</LINE>
	<LINE>possible regarding all the facts of the case, and to enclose whatever</LINE>
	<LINE>documents may throw light upon it.</LINE>
	<LINE>Gth. To see that every letter contains the full address of the writer, in</LINE>
	<LINE>order to ensure the retui-n of the letter, if the person to whom it is</LINE>
	<LINE>dii-ected cannot be found.</LINE>
